04/12/2002
KRANJSKA GORA, Slovenia -- Slovenia, Yugoslavia, Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina reached a provisional agreement Tuesday (3 December) on the use of the Sava River, though informed sources were quoted as saying that fine-tuning is still needed before the final document can be signed.Croatian Foreign Minister Tonino Picula said the agreement would provide for free navigation and joint care of the river. 
His Slovenian counterpart, Dimitrij Rupel, said the deal showed the four former rivals had put the past behind them and were moving forward to co-operation. 
Erhard Busek, the head of the Stabilisation Pact for Southeastern Europe, also praised the agreement. 
(AP, B92, Tanjug, FoNet, Television Slovenia, BBC - 03/12/02)
